				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Industria non coacta, cit&ograve; deferuescit.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Industriousness which is not driven onward will quickly grow cold.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nullibi morandum vltra Fortij mensem. Cui
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Joachim Fortius Ringelberg"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						a[e]quipollet Chrysotechni Septimana.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Chrysotechnus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Nowhere must a matter be delayed beyond a month of Fortius, <!-- CG: The meaning of this is unclear. -->
				with whom the week of Chrysotechnus is equally as strong.			
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						scit&egrave;.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Knowingly.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Cogendus sibi quisq[ue] quotidi&egrave;: ne quid extrema[e] sua[e] potestatis
						languescat.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Cogendus sibi"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="quid extrema[e] sua[e] potestatis"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Each man must collect himself daily, lest something of his utmost power diminish.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nam qui non crescit pro viribus, descrescit.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Indeed, he who does not grow in the face of other men will shrink.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="IT">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Paradosso generoso, oue necessario.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A generous paradox where necessary.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Item prouerbia Italorum, Heiuodi, Erasmi. In primisq[ue] ioci isti, et sales Domenici,
						Castillionis, Guatij, mensa[e] philosophica[e]: qua[e] Eutrapeli delitia[e].
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="John Heywood"/>
					<person name="Erasmus"/>
					<person name="Lodovico Domenichi"/>
					<person name="Castiglione"/>
					<person name="Stefano Guazzo"/>
					<person name="Eutrapelus"/>
					<book title="Mensa philosophica"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="prouerbia"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="ioci isti"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="sales"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Eutrapeli delitia[e]"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Likewise, the proverbs of the Italians, Heywood, Erasmus; and first, those jokes and witticisms of Domenichi,
				Castiglione, Guazzo, and the Mensa Philosophica, all of which are delights for Eutrapelus.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Vald&egrave; etiam ingenio conferunt Rabela[e]sius, et Arcadia Comitiss[a]e: Apologia Herodoti, et Loci
						communes Manlij: Sylua Nuptialis, et Bartasij diuini Hymni. Multo plus, qu&agrave;m omnes
						Italica[e] Oda[e], et discursus. Nihil Aretinus ad Rabela[e]sium.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Francois Rabelais"/>
					<person name="Johannes Jacobus Manlius"/>
					<person name="Guillaume Du Bartas"/>
					<person name="Pietro Aretino"/>
					<book title="Tthe Countess of Pembroke's Arcadia"/>
					<book title="Apologie pour HÃ©rodote"/>
					<book title="Loci communes"/>
					<book title="Sylva nuptialis"/>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				And by all means, Rabelais with his ingenuity and the Countess of Pembroke's Arcadia should be added, 
				as well as the Apology for Herodotus, the common places of Manlius, the 'Sylva nuptialis' and Bartas' divine hymns.
				These are much greater than all the odes and discourses of Italy. Aretino is nothing compared with Rabelais.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
